{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584166"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:40:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:40:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14415"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14415"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.04,0.52,0,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57237"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7110"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42696"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9861"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17147"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57237"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA healthy 25-year-old woman is participating in a marathon. Consider the cardiovascular changes that occur during continuous exercise.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following decreases during continuous exercise?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inotropy","Venous return","Total peripheral resistance","Cardiac output","End-diastolic volume"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring continuous exercise, \u003Cstrong\u003Etotal peripheral resistance\u003C/strong\u003E decreases to allow increased blood flow to active skeletal muscles through vasodilation of blood vessels in the working muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInotropy\u003C/strong\u003E increases due to sympathetic nervous system activation, enhancing the force of cardiac contraction. \u003Cstrong\u003EVenous return\u003C/strong\u003E increases due to the muscle pump effect and increased respiratory activity. \u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac output\u003C/strong\u003E increases to meet the elevated oxygen demands of exercising muscles. \u003Cstrong\u003EEnd-diastolic volume\u003C/strong\u003E increases due to the enhanced venous return, contributing to the increased stroke volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese cardiovascular adaptations work together to ensure adequate oxygen delivery to active tissues during exercise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["During continuous exercise, total peripheral resistance decreases to allow increased blood flow to active muscles.","Inotropy, venous return, cardiac output, and end-diastolic volume all increase during continuous exercise to meet increased metabolic demands."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Emery, C.F., Truong, E.A.K., Oliver, K.N. Physical Activity/Exercise and Cardiovascular Disease. In: Waldstein, S.R., Kop, W.J., Suarez, E.C., Lovallo, W.R., Katzel, L.I. (eds) Handbook of Cardiovascular Behavioral Medicine. 2022. Springer, New York, NY. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1007/978-0-387-85960-6_16","Massaferri R, Matos-Santos L, Farinatti P, Monteiro WD. Hemodynamic Responses and Perceived Exertion During Continuous and Discon